*Wrong escaping of single quote in python syntax*

 

*Steps to Reproduce*
 # Create review comment with python syntax containing single quote :// code placeholder 

{noformat}
{code:python} 
def function(parameter):
   dict_ = {1: 'test', 2: 'another'}
   print(dict_[2])
{code}
{noformat}

h3. Expected result

A correctly rendered single quote.
{code:java}
def function(parameter):
   dict_ = {1: 'test', 2: 'another'}
   print(dict_[2])
{code}

h3. Actual Result

A single quote is replaced by escape sequence.

{noformat}
 def function(parameter):
   dict_ = {1: &#39;test', 2: 'another'}
   print(dict_[2])   
{noformat}
 

*Workaround*

Use \{code:java} instead of \{code:python} in review comments

There is a CSS rule that sets outline width on an extensive set of elements to 0:

{code}
html, body, div, span, applet, object, iframe, h1, h5, h6, blockquote, pre, a, abbr, acronym, address,
big, cite, code, del, dfn, em, font, img, ins, kbd, q, s, samp, small, strike, strong, sub, sup, tt, var, b, u, i,
center, dl, dt, dd, ol, ul, li, fieldset, form, label, legend, table, caption, tbody, tfoot, thead, tr, th, td {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    border: 0;
    outline: 0;
    vertical-align: baseline;
    background: transparent;
}
{code}

Among other effects, this causes focused hyperlink elements to lose their dotted outline. As a result, the user cannot see where the focus is and is effectively unable to navigate the page using keyboard only.

This is an accessibility issue. Not everyone can use a mouse or other pointing device.
